y. Luther’s conflict with Rome forced him to address the issue of papal authority, but on his own time, he focused on encouraging lay Christians to embrace a simpler, self-sacrificing faith. In these pastoral writings, he criticized theologians and church officials for leading people astray with a reliance on religious works, and he began to lay the foundation for a reformed Christian piety.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aChristian life. 0aPiety. 0aSpiritual lifexChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311074523840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271091334?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271091334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271091334/original  a978-3-11-074523-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK